zation2star  aThe central question explored in this volume is: How is humor multimodally produced, perceived, responded to, and negotiated? To this end, it offers a panorama of linguistic research on multimodal and interactional humor, based on different theoretical frameworks, corpora, and methodologies. Humor is considered as an activity that is interactionally achieved, regardless of whether the interaction in which it is embedded is face-to-face, computer-mediated, with a human or a robot, oral or written. The aim is to analyze both the linguistic resources of the participants (such as their lexicon, prosody, gestures, gazes, or smiles) and the semiotic resources that social networks and instant messaging platforms offer them (such as memes, gifs, or emojis).  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 4aHumor und Interaktion. 4aMultimodalität. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Communication Studies.2bisacsh  aInteractional Humor.  aMultimodal Resources.  aMultimodality.1 aAndré, Elisabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAttardo, Salvatore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrône, Geert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aChen, Xinren, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDodane, Christelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErgül, Hilal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGironzetti, Elisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaugh, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKiderle, Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKramer, Kevin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/rel